<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1902,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1902,1923]" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="A. Flowering" authorityName="A. Flowering" box="[273,613,1903,1924]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis box="[273,481,1903,1924]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Anathallis amazonica</emphasis>
A. Flowering
</taxonomicName>
habit with oblanceolate leaves. B. Fruiting habit with elliptic leaves. C. Tridenticulate leaf apex. D. Acute distended leaf apex. E. Acute twitched leaf apex. F. Detail of the inflorescence. G. Dissected perianth. H. Lip ciliate on the base (
<emphasis box="[339,482,1962,1983]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">J. da Cruz 242</emphasis>
). I. Lip entirely ciliate (
<emphasis box="[716,858,1962,1983]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">J. da Cruz 240</emphasis>
). J. Lip not ciliate (
<emphasis box="[1057,1200,1962,1983]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">J. da Cruz 243</emphasis>
). K. Column. Drawn by 
<taxonomicName authority="Carvalho." box="[151,320,1991,2012]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Regina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Regina Carvalho.</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,1454]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
Epiphytic, subrepent herb. Roots fasciculate, about 0.5–1.0 mm wide. Rhizome 
<quantity box="[1098,1240,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.9">0.9–1.1 mm</quantity>
wide, branched. Secondary stem 2.2–5.1 × 
<quantity box="[469,616,190,216]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.4">0.4–0.7 mm</quantity>
, cylindrical, unifoliate, concealed by one white to gray, close-fitting, membranaceous sheath, 2.5–5.0 mm long, acute or obtuse apex, striate, entire margin. Leaf 5.0–19.0 × 1.2–3.0 mm, oblanceolate to elliptic, pale green, coriaceous, glabrous, acute apex, rarely minutely tridenticulate, attenuate to obtuse base, entire margin. Inflorescence terminal, congested, fasciculate, erect; peduncle and rachis inconspicuous; floral bracts about 1.0– 
<quantity box="[849,935,345,371]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
long, amplexicaul, membranaceous, acute to acuminate apex, entire margin. Flowers 1–4, reddish maroon (according to the collector), these opening successively; pedicellate ovary 1.2–1.5 × 
<quantity box="[652,800,422,448]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="0.2" valueMax="0.3" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.3 mm</quantity>
; dorsal sepal 3.0–3.5 × 
<quantity box="[1086,1233,422,448]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="1.05" valueMax="1.3" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.3 mm</quantity>
, free, lanceolate, membranaceous, acute apex, entire margin, 3-nerved; lateral sepals 3.0–3.5 × 0.6–1.0 mm, connate up to ¼ from base, lanceolate, sub-falcate, membranaceous, acute apex, entire margin, 3-nerved, forming a small mentum with the column foot; petals 1.8–2.6 × 
<quantity box="[805,968,538,564]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="0.44999999999999996" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.6 mm</quantity>
, free, narrow elliptic, sub-falcate, membranaceous, acute to rounded apex, entire margin, 1-nerved; lip 1.5–2.0 × 
<quantity box="[1119,1267,577,603]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="0.4" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.5 mm</quantity>
, free, oblong, rounded apex, with two basal appendages, ciliate margin from the base up to the middle, entirely ciliate or sometimes not ciliate, papillose, 3-nerved, articulated with the column foot; column about 1.0– 
<quantity box="[1279,1367,654,680]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
long, broadly winged, clinandrium 5-dentate, obtuse apex, entire margin, column foot about 
<quantity box="[1207,1299,693,719]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
long. Fruit 2.5–3.0 × 
<quantity box="[270,413,732,758]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="1.35" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.2">1.2–1.5 mm</quantity>
, obovoid, glabrous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,1454]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,526,770,796]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Distribution and Ecology:</emphasis>
—This species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1001,1051,770,796]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">type</typeStatus>
locality, in the central Brazilian Amazon, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[367,498,809,835]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
. The vegetation in the area is characterized by moist tropical lowland forest, locally called 
<emphasis box="[319,449,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">terra firme</emphasis>
forest (
<bibRefCitation author="Lima, S. O. F. &amp; Martins, M. B. &amp; Prudente, A. L. C. &amp; Montag, L. F. A. &amp; Monnerat, M. C. &amp; Cabral, P. R. &amp; Rosario, D. A. P." box="[541,747,848,874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" refId="ref1804" refString="Lima, S. O. F., Martins, M. B., Prudente, A. L. C., Montag, L. F. A., Monnerat, M. C., Cabral, P. R., Rosario, D. A. P. (2008) Biodiversidade na Provincia Petrolifera de Urucu. PETROBRAS, CENPES, Rio de Janeiro, 194 pp." type="book" year="2008">
Lima 
<emphasis box="[614,675,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
). The flowering period is poorly known, but based on the specimens cited, flowers can be observed from February to July.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,1454]" box="[198,1406,925,951]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,925,951]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Etymology:</emphasis>
—This new species is named on behalf of the area of occurrence, Brazilian Amazon basin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,1454]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,520,963,989]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Morphological affinities:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName box="[549,813,964,989]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis box="[549,813,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Anathallis amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically related to species placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Luer" authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="2006" box="[151,299,1002,1027]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Panmorphia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,299,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Panmorphia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Luer. The new species has a subrepent habit like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Carnevali &amp; Ramirez" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[932,1040,1002,1027]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holstii">
<emphasis box="[932,1040,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. holstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Grisebach" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1099,1290,1002,1027]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polygonoides">
<emphasis box="[1099,1290,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. polygonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Leaf shape appears to vary: the leaves on the mature branches are oblanceolate like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Swartz" baseAuthorityYear="1788" box="[1058,1265,1041,1066]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sertularioides">
<emphasis box="[1058,1265,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. sertularioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while on the immature branches they are elliptic as is found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Carnevali &amp; Ramirez" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[744,851,1080,1105]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holstii">
<emphasis box="[744,851,1080,1105]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. holstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Grisebach" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[909,1100,1080,1105]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polygonoides">
<emphasis box="[909,1100,1080,1105]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. polygonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The inflorescences have an inconspicuous peduncle and the flowers appear to arise from the same point like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Carnevali &amp; Ramirez" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[1083,1187,1119,1144]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holstii">
<emphasis box="[1083,1187,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. holstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1242,1436,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Grisebach" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1242,1432,1119,1144]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polygonoides">A. polygonoides</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In 
<emphasis box="[183,386,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Swartz" baseAuthorityYear="1788" box="[183,381,1157,1182]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sertularioides">A. sertularioides</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the inflorescence is long pedunculate. The flowers on 
<taxonomicName box="[1033,1193,1157,1182]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis box="[1033,1193,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have narrow elliptic petals like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Swartz" baseAuthorityYear="1788" box="[285,489,1196,1221]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sertularioides">
<emphasis box="[285,489,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. sertularioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pridgeon &amp; Chase" authorityYear="2001" baseAuthorityName="Grisebach" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[553,749,1196,1221]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polygonoides">
<emphasis box="[553,749,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. polygonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Carnevali &amp; Ramirez" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[811,922,1196,1221]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holstii">
<emphasis box="[811,922,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. holstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have broadly elliptic petals. The lip of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Anathallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="15">A. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is oblong and ciliate from the base up to the middle, entirely ciliate or sometimes not ciliate. However, the three related species have a slightly trilobed to clearly trilobed lip with an entire margin (
<tableCitation box="[1332,1419,1273,1299]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,1508,1532]" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparison of morphological features of A. amazonica and related species." pageId="2" pageNumber="15">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
